To create the CMidi object:

CMidi(string portName = "", bool bBlockingMode = true);
  Creates a CMidi object, opening the MIDI device port or virtual input file

  Parameters:
  string portName       May designate port, or allow CMidi to find "hw:?,0,1",
                        where '?' is a digit in the range 1 to 4
  bool bBlockingMode    Determines whether read() blocks.
                        If false, read() will return a negative number -11 if no
                        MIDI output from device was available to read.

int open(bool bBlockingMode = true, bool bSilent = false)
  Opens the MIDI device port or virtual input file.
  GENERALLY, DO NOT CALL, CMidi (above) will call

  Parameters:
  bool bBlockingMode    See above
  bool bSilent          If true, output no logging information

int write(string& s)
  Writes bytes to the CMidi object.
  Note that NULLs can be embedded in s for writing. MIDI uses byte values of 0.

  Parameters:
  string& s   The output string to write to CMidi object (may be empty)

  RETURN:
    >= 0  The number of bytes written
    < 0   Write was unsuccessful (return is status code)

int read()
  Read a character from the CMidi object (device port or virtual port)
  No parameters

  RETURN:
    >= 0  The next byte read from CMidi object
    -11   If non-blocking, no character available to read
    < 0   Read was unsuccessful
             represents an error if not -11 in non-blocking mode

Example source application (simply loopback demo):

midiloop.cpp - echos MIDI notes, transposed (uses blocking mode)
               credit to Craig Stuart <craig@ccrma.stanford.edu> for midiecho.c
               which was heavily referenced to create midiloop.cpp using the
               CMidi class.
